# Using Transcriptomics for biomarker discovery of breast cancers

## The Central dogma of molecular biology

There is quite a lot of molecular data that we can gain from different cells in our bodies. The genetic information codified in DNA (genome) is then transcribed into RNA (transcriptome) that is then translated into proteins (proteome) which then gets broken down into metabolites (metabolome). Understanding this process is crucial to identify where errors like mutations or transcription errors that can lead to cancer and that can be used for biomarker discovery. All of those types of data can be gained from clinical samples of healthy and diseased individuals. The old concept of “one-gene/one-protein/one-function” is now being corrected as the high-throughput sequencing technologies have revolutionized the fields of genomics and transcriptomics by shifting the old approach of focusing on single genes or mutations to focusing on the study of the entire genome.(1)  The discovery of biomarkers is important for early detection, prognosis, and personalized treatment.

## The data

Cancer-specific online omics databases and clinical databases are publicly available and are great sources for novel biomarker discovery for different cancers.(1) These include:  
\-          	The Cancer Genome Atlas (TCGA) that includes genomic, epigenomic, transcriptomic, and proteomic data from thousands of cancer patients and that has cataloged genetic mutations responsible for cancer.(2)  
\-          	Catalogue Of Somatic Mutations In Cancer (COSMIC) which includes data on mutations, gene fusions, copy number variations. (3)

## The science of Transcriptomics

Transcriptomics analysis is the sequencing of all the coding and non-coding RNAs transcribed in a tissue or a cell in either physiological or pathological states.  
We can use single cell DNA/RNA sequencing (scDNA/RNA-seq) to tell us about the cellular and molecular information of a BC cell. Transcriptomics has provided insights into the molecular mechanisms of BC development and progression and investigation of biomarkers and possible treatment targets.(4)  
 

## Identification of biomarkers

An example is polyadenylation(APA) (a post-transcriptional change in 3’UTR that alters it’s length and therefore affects the tumor cell proliferation), the majority of patients with BC have a shortened 3’UTR.(4)  
Another example is the *ETV6* gene which is selectively activated in five molecular cellular subtypes, its overexpression is linked to a worse prognosis in TNBC patients. This can be used as a therapeutic target. (4)

## Conclusion

Applying transcriptomics technologies to investigate novel biomarkers and potential therapeutic targets can help us advance our understanding of different types and subtypes of breast cancers as well as provide data for investigating future treatments.
